item.title: Mystery surrounds missing Vic campers
item.description: Two friends missing in Victoria's high country for a month set off for the camping trip together without their families knowledge and could have met with foul play, police fear.

item.title: Business pushing case for company tax cuts
item.description: Big business has made a renewed push for company tax cuts as the federal government looks at a sweeping post-pandemic economic reform agenda.

item.title: Queensland parliament returns for one day
item.description: Parliament has resumed for one day in Queensland for politicians to push through changes to tenancy laws during the COVID-19 crisis.

item.title: Zero Qld COVID cases but restrictions stay
item.description: Queensland has recorded zero coronavirus cases for the second time this week as the health minister urged aged care homes' bosses to allow loved ones to visit.

item.title: Australian virus death toll rises to 74
item.description: Australia's coronavirus death toll has reached 74 but the rate of new infections continues to fall prompting eased restrictions on elective surgeries.

item.title: Cuomo says Trump talk ‘honest and open’
item.description: New York Governor Andrew Cuomo says he has had a "functional and effective" conversation with President Donald Trump and tried to keep the focus on coronavirus testing and state budget problems.

item.title: Thousands of airport staff facing the sack
item.description: Thousands of airport goundstaff are facing the sack as the coronavirus pandemic suffocates the aviation industry.

item.title: China’s Dutton attack unhelpful: treasurer
item.description: Treasurer Josh Frydenberg has hit back at China's attack on Home Affairs Minister Peter Dutton after he was accused of parroting US lines.

item.title: COVID-19 poker machine loss up to $1.5b
item.description: Poker machine gamblers likely saved up to $1.5 billion in the weeks since pubs, clubs and casinos have been closed because of coronavirus restrictions.

item.title: Islamists kill 52 villagers in Mozambique
item.description: About 52 villagers in Mozambique's troubled northernmost province were killed by Islamist insurgents on April 7 after they refused to be recruited to their ranks, police say.
